r-Man, Thor, and Deadpool. Cancer, the authors argue, troubles the binaries of good and evil because it is the ultimate nemesis within a genre replete with magic, mutants, and multiverses. They draw from gender theory, disability studies, and cultural theory to demonstrate how cancer in comics enables an examination of power and responsibility, key terms in Marvel’s superhero universe. As the only full-length study on cancer in the Marvel universe, The Cancer Plot is an appealing and original work that will be of interest to scholars across the humanities, particularly those working in the health humanities, cultural theory, and literature, as well as avid comics readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCancer in literature. 0aComic books, strips, etc.zUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aGraphic medicine (Comic books). 0aSuperheroes in comics. 4aArt & Performance / Art & Design. 4aArt & Performance. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comics & Graphic Novels.2bisacsh  aCancer.  aCaptain Marvel.  aComics Studies.  aComics.  aDeadpool.  aDeath.  aDisability Studies.  aDisease.  aGraphic Medicine.  aGraphic Novels.  aHealing.  aHealth.  aLiterary Analysis.  aMedical Humanities.  aPopular Culture.  aSpiderman.  aSuperhero.  aTerminal illness.  aThor.1 aWoodman, Dorothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978177212717140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781772127171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781772127171/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles